Banks are about to get walloped by the coronavirus pandemic.
Credit swaps, a type of default insurance, allow derivatives traders to hedge or speculate on creditworthiness.
Swaps linked to European banks like Italy’s Unicredit and Germany’s Deutsche Bank remain much more elevated.
The change in credit swaps suggests derivatives traders are optimistic that government aid will successfully support bank customers and the broader economy.
“There’s no guarantee, obviously, that continues as we go through the quarter,” Solomon said this week of the heavy trading volume.